Local Engagement as a Counter to Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies have been shaken to their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing electoral defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former president Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar everywhere in the West.
The leadership of once-dominant parties swings between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their supporters as "pitiable," as Hillary Clinton did just before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too scared in the face of the populist tide to launch a counterattack.
Neither denial nor complacency will resolve the stalemate political situation.
Progressives must reposition themselves, and this begins with a diagnosis of the shortcomings of traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the worsening environmental crises, the increasing geographic inequality, the tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that really matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they stand alone in the forest and wonder where everyone has gone.
Social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has gone off track.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and the politics of governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the growing disparity in income and other indicators between a few wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
Yet until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national head of government had implemented tax cuts based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of the French GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters rather than only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In the year 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the pollsters became the basis for Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless women's statements about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual harassment of women, and Macron promised to address the issue if elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of his opponents' jokes; however, the laughter quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
Traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and encourage candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace, consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to gain and maintain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological edge over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to elections, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Citizens today refuse to be mere consumers of state politics.
Along with a higher level of education, new demands for participation emerged.
The voters want to be treated as political actors in their own right, not as pawns in the game of others.
Furthermore, governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we had to learn over the two years we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
The today's most important political challenges – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions solely from national governments.
These challenges require deep cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbency bonus and entrenched support networks.
Those who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well do not need a centuries-old party apparatus.
Political movements must therefore be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures, not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed with people on the ground.
At La République En Marche!, we refer to this as local citizen projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering solutions tailored to local problems, thereby strengthening communities.
Such projects should today be considered indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding ways for political and civic engagement will be crucial to its attractiveness.
And by demonstrating their reform policies "live" every day, the parties have already laid the groundwork for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what is being said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over.
Reconnecting with voters' concerns therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need a progressive politics on the ground.
